Project: Wrangling and Analyze Data¶

Data Gathering¶

# Unable to gain access to the twitter api, however, made use of the file provided in the classroom for the tweet.
# Below is the link code used to dowload the tweet_json.txt file used in the analysis
"""
import tweepy
from tweepy import OAuthHandler
import json
from timeit import default_timer as timer

# Query Twitter API for each tweet in the Twitter archive and save JSON in a text file
# These are hidden to comply with Twitter's API terms and conditions
consumer_key = 'HIDDEN'
consumer_secret = 'HIDDEN'
access_token = 'HIDDEN'
access_secret = 'HIDDEN'

auth = OAuthHandler(consumer_key, consumer_secret)
auth.set_access_token(access_token, access_secret)

api = tweepy.API(auth, wait_on_rate_limit=True)

tweet_ids = df_direct.tweet_id.values
len(tweet_ids)

# Query Twitter's API for JSON data for each tweet ID in the Twitter archive
count = 0
fails_dict = {}
start = timer()
# Save each tweet's returned JSON as a new line in a .txt file
with open('tweet_json.txt', 'w') as outfile:
    # This loop will likely take 20-30 minutes to run because of Twitter's rate limit
    for tweet_id in tweet_ids:
        count += 1
        print(str(count) + ": " + str(tweet_id))
        try:
            tweet = api.get_status(tweet_id, tweet_mode='extended')
            print("Success")
            json.dump(tweet._json, outfile)
            outfile.write('\n')
        except tweepy.TweepError as e:
            print("Fail")
            fails_dict[tweet_id] = e
            pass
end = timer()
print(end - start)
print(fails_dict)

In [11]:
add_list = []
with open('tweet-json.txt', encoding='utf-8') as file:
    for line in file:
        line = json.loads(file.readline()) #https://www.freecodecamp.org/news/python-json-how-to-convert-a-string-to-json/
        tweet_id = line['id']
        retweet_count = line['retweet_count']
        favorite_count = line['favorite_count']
        retweeted = line['retweeted']
        

        # Append to list of dictionaries
        add_list.append({'tweet_id': tweet_id,
                        'retweet_count': retweet_count,
                        'favorite_count': favorite_count,
                        'retweeted': retweeted})
add_info = pd.DataFrame(add_list, columns = ['tweet_id', 'retweet_count', 'favorite_count', 'retweeted'])

Assessing Data¶

In this section, detect and document at least eight (8) quality issues and two (2) tidiness issue. You must use both visual assessment programmatic assessement to assess the data.

Note: pay attention to the following key points when you access the data.

  • You only want original ratings (no retweets) that have images. Though there are 5000+ tweets in the dataset, not all are dog ratings and some are retweets.
  • Assessing and cleaning the entire dataset completely would require a lot of time, and is not necessary to practice and demonstrate your skills in data wrangling. Therefore, the requirements of this project are only to assess and clean at least 8 quality issues and at least 2 tidiness issues in this dataset.
  • The fact that the rating numerators are greater than the denominators does not need to be cleaned. This unique rating system is a big part of the popularity of WeRateDogs.
  • You do not need to gather the tweets beyond August 1st, 2017. You can, but note that you won't be able to gather the image predictions for these tweets since you don't have access to the algorithm used.

Quality issues¶

twitter_archive table¶

  1. The rating_numerator and rating_denominator from tweet text doesn't match the ratings in the body of text, possibly due to other numbers in text e.g. index 45, other listed and identified in the assessing stage

  2. Some entries are retweets characterised by retweeted_status_id

  3. Some entries are replies characterised by in_reply_to_status_id

  4. Tweet post found in index 2338 is not a dog. Some tweets are not to rate dogs e.g. tweet in index 315. Others identified, and have been listed in the issue section

  5. Missing expanded_url (column containing the picture url of the dogs) records

  6. Some rating_denominators are less or greater that 10

  7. Large amount of missing data and incorrectly captured data for the name variable

  8. timestamp is not it datetime

  9. The source entries can be shorter text

image_pred table¶

  1. Duplicated jpg_urls about 66 records

Tidiness issues¶

  1. retweet_count, favourite_count and columns in the image_pred table should be part of the twitter_archive table1.
  2. In the twitter_archive table, the are 4 columns to characterise the dogs into 'doggo', 'floofer', 'pupper' and 'puppo' whereas one column is needed. NB. The ratio of number of WeRate Dog Classification Records to the size of the total dataset is about 1%

Cleaning Data¶

In this section, clean all of the issues you documented while assessing.

Note: Make a copy of the original data before cleaning. Cleaning includes merging individual pieces of data according to the rules of tidy data. The result should be a high-quality and tidy master pandas DataFrame (or DataFrames, if appropriate).

Issue #5 & #6: The rating_numerator from tweet text doesn't match the ratings in the body of text, possibly due to other numbers in text e.g. index 45, other listed and identified in the assessing stage. Some rating_denominators are less or greater that 10¶

Define¶

Replace all the ratings (numerator & denominator) identified in the assessment stage with the correct values. Remove other rating_denominators not equal to 10 to allow for easy comparison. Also, remove numerators ratings less than 5 (most likely not dog posts) and ratings greater than 15 to remove outliers

Issue #7: In the twitter_archive table, the are 4 columns to characterise the dogs into doggo, floofer, pupper and puppo whereas one column is needed. The ratio of number of WeRate Dog Classification Records to the size of the total dataset is about 1%¶

Define¶

Replace "None" values with an empty string, merge all 4 columns into a new stage column. Replace the Null/empty columns with N/A to protect against deletion in further cleaning operations. Drop the doggo, floofer, pupper and puppocolumns

Code¶

In [77]:
#Ref = Reviewer
twitter_archive_clean.doggo.replace('None', '', inplace=True) 
twitter_archive_clean.floofer.replace('None', '', inplace=True)
twitter_archive_clean.pupper.replace('None', '', inplace=True)
twitter_archive_clean.puppo.replace('None', '', inplace=True)

#Combine stage columns.
twitter_archive_clean['stage'] = twitter_archive_clean.doggo + twitter_archive_clean.floofer + twitter_archive_clean.pupper + twitter_archive_clean.puppo

#Format entries with multiple dog stages

twitter_archive_clean.loc[twitter_archive_clean.stage == 'doggopupper', 'stage'] = 'doggo,pupper' 
twitter_archive_clean.loc[twitter_archive_clean.stage == 'doggopuppo', 'stage'] = 'doggo,puppo' 
twitter_archive_clean.loc[twitter_archive_clean.stage == 'doggofloofer', 'stage'] = 'doggo,floofer'

#to prevent the rows without stage classification from being dropped in further cleaning actions as  stage classificatication data is less than 1%
twitter_archive_clean.loc[twitter_archive_clean.stage == '', 'stage'] = 'N/A'
In [78]:
#drop doggo, floofer, pupper and puppo columns
twitter_archive_clean = twitter_archive_clean.drop(['doggo', 'floofer', 'pupper', 'puppo'], axis =1)

Issue #9: The source entries can be shorter text¶

Define¶

Replace the 4 unique values in source(refers to the utility used to post the tweet) column with shorter names:

'<a href="http://twitter.com/download/iphone" rel="nofollow">Twitter for iPhone</a>' - iPhone

'<a href="http://twitter.com" rel="nofollow">Twitter Web Client</a>' - Web

'<a href="http://vine.co" rel="nofollow">Vine - Make a Scene</a>' - Vine

'<a href="https://about.twitter.com/products/tweetdeck" rel="nofollow">TweetDeck</a>' - TweetDeck

Code¶

In [84]:
twitter_archive_clean = twitter_archive_clean.replace({'<a href="http://twitter.com/download/iphone" rel="nofollow">Twitter for iPhone</a>': 'iPhone',
       '<a href="http://twitter.com" rel="nofollow">Twitter Web Client</a>': 'Web',
       '<a href="http://vine.co" rel="nofollow">Vine - Make a Scene</a>': 'Vine',
       '<a href="https://about.twitter.com/products/tweetdeck" rel="nofollow">TweetDeck</a>': 'TweetDeck'})

Test¶

In [85]:
twitter_archive_clean['source'].unique()
Out[85]:
array(['iPhone', 'Web', 'Vine', 'TweetDeck'], dtype=object)

Issue #11 & #12: retweet_count, favourite_count and columns in the image_pred table should be part of the twitter_archive table. Duplicated jpg_urls about 66 records¶

Define¶

Join all three tables and remove the null values from the table. Remove duplicated jpg_url

Code¶

In [89]:
table1 = twitter_archive_clean.merge(image_pred_clean, how = 'left', on = 'tweet_id')
In [90]:
table2 = table1.merge(add_info_clean, how ='left', on ='tweet_id')
In [91]:
table2.dropna(inplace =True)

Insights:¶

  1. Based on the cleaned data, 98% of the tweets from the WeRateDogs account were from an iPhone
  2. 12/10 was the most popular rating used on the account Whereas 6/10, was the least popular rating on the account
  3. There is a positive correlation between Retweet/Favorite Count and WeRateDog Rating for WeRateDog Rating greater than 9/10, while there is no correlation for ratings less than 9/10

  4. Golden retrievers, Labrador retrievers, and Pembroke breeds are the most reviewed dog breed by WeRateDog Twitter account. In terms of the WeRateDogs Rating, the highest retweeted/favorited dog breeds are:

     a. 13/10 : English Springer
 b. 12/10 : Italian Greyhound
 c. 11/10  : Great Pyrenees
  5. 12 - 2 a.m. were popular times for tweets from the WeRateDog Twitter account. However, the Twitter account tweeted mainly between 12 - 5 a.m. and 3 - 11 p.m. The mean highest retweet/favorite count occurred at 6 a.m.
  6. The retweet/favorite count also increased on yearly basis, indicating increased popularity of the Twitter account

Visualization¶

Visualizations are embedded in the analysis section
